      <h2 id="project-admin">Project Administration</h2>
      <h4>Communications Plan</h4>
      <p>The project manager will be responsible for the creation of an internal communications plan. The plan will detail how the project team keeps the appropriate individuals informed on important project related status and activities.</p>

      <h4>Scope Management Plan</h4>
      <p>The project team, particularly the project managers and assigned business analysts, will work with the vendor to manage the overall scope of the project. The initial project scope will be based on an agreed upon set of requirements and will act
        as a baseline to form the project schedule. As the project progresses, all deviations from the baseline requirements will follow the established change management process.</p>

      <h4>Quality Management Plan</h4>
      <p>The project manager and QA lead will be responsible for creating a quality management plan. The plan will identify the project’s key quality requirements and methods the team will use to verify the solution. As the solution entered UAT, the plan
        will outline the processes used to manage the identified defects in detail. In addition, the plan will detail the acceptance criteria for performance, security, and recovery testing efforts.</p>

      <h4>Change Management Plan</h4>
      <p>The project manager will create a change management plan that describes how the team will manage changes to the project’s scope. This will include a method to categorize and prioritize changes based on their identified need and risk. In addition,
        an escalation process will be form to ensure that the project’s sponsor and key stakeholders are involved in any significant decisions regarding cost, schedule, or quality.</p>

      <h4>Human Resource Plan</h4>
      <p>The project manager will create a human resource plan that will identify the key project roles and responsibilities of the team members during the project. In addition, the plan will contain a project organizational chart and a staffing management
        plan. The staffing plan will identify project resource needs in terms on skillsets and timelines.</p>


      <h2 id="plans">Implementation and Continued Maintenance and Project Closure Plan</h2>

      <h4>Production Systems Impact</h4>
      <p>Upon implementation of the new system, the existing legacy HR system will be shutdown.</p>

      <h4>Required Downtime</h4>
      <p>The implementation of the new system is scheduled to occur over the weekend between 11/13/15 – 11/15/15 to minimize the operation impact of the change. During this timeframe all HR related systems will be unavailable.</p>

      <h4>Deployment Communication</h4>
      <p>The organization will communicate the deployment schedule and any potential operation impacts to the affected staff on a scheduled basis leading up to the implementation date.</p>

      <h4>Deployment Model</h4>
      <p>The plan is to deploy the new HR new system as a single, clean cutover from the existing legacy systems.</p>

      <h4>Support and Maintenance</h4>
      <p>The plan is to utilize the organization’s existing support center and ticketing system to manage all post-produciton system issues. Once logged, the organization’s IT staff will triage the issues and escalate any support issues to the supporting
        software vendor if deemed necessary.</p>

      <h4>Project Closure</h4>
      <p>Once deployed into the production environment successfully, the project sponsor will formally approve the project deliverables and the project manager will begin the process of closing out the project. However if issues occur that cannot be remediated
        acceptability during the course of the project, the sponsor has the ability to terminate the project at any time.</p>

